From a34202778a7a815fb0cec9b147f1716f8a7fecd6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Paul Meyer <katexochen0@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Apr 2026 21:27:11 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] Use fd-relative syscalls for backing-FS access
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

In multi-user mode, Guard::drop_privileges() sets the thread's euid
to the FUSE caller before accessing the backing filesystem.  Path-
based syscalls like open(root + path) re-check search permission on
every component, failing with EACCES when an intermediate directory
is not traversable by the caller (e.g. a root-owned 0700 temp dir
that contains a user-owned subdirectory).

Replace all path-based syscalls with fd-relative equivalents:

  resolve_parent(): walk ancestor components as root using openat()
  to obtain an O_PATH fd to the parent directory.  Used by operations
  that create or delete entries (mkdir, unlink, create, …).

  resolve_target(): additionally open the leaf itself as root.  Used
  by operations that access an existing target (stat, open, chmod, …)
  where the caller may lack search permission on the parent.

After resolution, drop_privileges() runs and the operation executes
relative to the pinned fd.  For operations without *at() variants
(xattrs) or where the parent fd cannot be used directly (chmod,
chown, utimens, open, truncate), /proc/self/fd/N is used to refer
to the O_PATH fd.  Since the O_PATH fd is obtained with O_NOFOLLOW,
the follow-symlink variants (chown, setxattr, utimensat without
AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW) are used on the /proc/self/fd/N path — the
procfs magic symlink must be followed to reach the pinned target.

This preserves per-file authorization: the caller still needs the
appropriate permission on the target itself (e.g. file ownership for
chmod, write permission for open).  Only ancestor search permission
checks are bypassed, which is correct because the FUSE kernel module
already authorized the request before forwarding it to the daemon.

